// SOURCE: Source Files/Intergrations/Fusion Intergrations 2/Fusion Unified  Monolith/Fusion Unified Master Documentation.txt
// NOTE: Integrated into the Fusion FSN tree for migration traceability.
// CONTENT:
// Fusion Unified: The Monolithic Toolchain for Fusion & RustVersion: 3.4.1 (Unified)Date: 2025-10-26Status: Production Ready1. Product Info SheetOverviewFusion Unified is the official, next-generation build system and toolchain for the Fusion programming language. It is designed to be the backbone of the Fusion ecosystem while maintaining complete backward compatibility with Rust.It fundamentally reimagines the development lifecycle by collapsing separate tools—dependency resolution, compilation, security auditing, testing, and language server intelligence—into a single, high-performance, shared-memory process that serves both languages seamlessly.The ProblemTraditional workflows, particularly in the Rust ecosystem, suffer from "Split-Brain" issues:cargo builds the dependency graph.rust-analyzer re-parses the code separately, doubling memory usage.cargo-audit runs as a post-process, catching security issues only after the build.Fusion developers require a toolchain that handles modern language features natively without legacy baggage.The Fusion SolutionFusion runs as a Monolithic Daemon. It builds a single in-memory representation of your project state (FusionState), whether the source is Fusion (.fus) or Rust (.rs). The Builder writes to this state; the Auditor checks it in real-time; the Language Server (LSP) reads from it instantly (Zero-Copy); and the Runner executes the final binary, piping output to a unified TUI dashboard.Key CapabilitiesPolyglot Core: Native support for the Fusion language with a zero-overhead compatibility layer for Rust crates (Cargo.toml).Flux-Resolve: GPU-accelerated dependency resolution using CUDA for massive graphs.Shift-Left Security: Vulnerability checks happen during resolution. Unsafe crates are rejected before download.Zero-Copy Intelligence: The IDE gets diagnostics directly from the compiler's memory, reducing latency by 40%.Self-Optimizing LSP: Adaptive L1 caching learns your most-queried symbols and promotes them to thread-local storage.Unified TUI: A single terminal window for build progress, security alerts, and application runtime logs.2. User GuideInstallationFusion is distributed as a single static binary.# Install via bootstrap
// curl -fsSL [https://fusion.dev/install](https://fusion.dev/install) | sh
// 
// # Verify installation
// fusion --version
// # Output: Fusion Unified v3.4.1 (Target: Fusion/Rust + CUDA)
// 
// The run Command (Recommended)The primary workflow. This command handles the entire lifecycle: Resolve -> Audit -> Build -> Test -> Execute.fusion run
// 
// What you will see (TUI Dashboard):[Fusion] Running Target (PID: 12345)...
// --------------------------------------------------
//  > Fusion App v1.0 Starting...
//  > Listening on port 8080
//  > [LSP Alert] src/main.fus:12: Unused variable `x`
//  > Connection received from 127.0.0.1
// 
// Other Commands|| Command | Description || fusion check | New! Fast semantic analysis. Checks types and audit status without generating binaries. || fusion build | Stops after the compilation phase. Compiles .fus and .rs sources. || fusion run | Full pipeline: Resolve -> Audit -> Build -> Test -> Execute. || fusion audit | Runs only the security scanning module against the dependency graph. || fusion watch | Daemon mode. Watches file system, rebuilds on change, and serves LSP requests. || fusion agent | Advanced. Spawns a dedicated, single-purpose agent process. |IDE Configuration (VS Code)Set your client to point to the Fusion binary. Fusion implements the standard Language Server Protocol (LSP) for both Fusion and Rust files.{
//   "fusion-client.engine.path": "/usr/local/bin/fusion",
//   "fusion-client.engine.args": ["watch"]
// }
// 
// 3. Product GuideDesign Philosophy"Fusion First, Rust Compatible." Fusion Unified is built to power the next generation of systems programming with the Fusion language. However, it respects the vast ecosystem of Rust. You can mix Fusion code with Rust dependencies effortlessly, or use it as a drop-in replacement for Cargo in pure Rust projects.Roadmapv3.4 (Current):Autonomous Agents: Dedicated processes (Sentry, Forge, Drive, Nexus) for specialized tasks.Fusion Check: Fast-pass semantic analysis command.Unified TUI Dashboard.v3.5 (Planned):Cloud Fusion: Remote caching of build artifacts to S3/GCS.Interop Bridge: Auto-generation of FFI bindings between Fusion and Rust modules.v4.0 (Future):Fusion IR: A custom intermediate representation optimized for incremental builds, bypassing LLVM for debug builds.4. Advanced Features: Autonomous AgentsFusion v3.4 introduces Dedicated Agents. These are specialized, isolated workers that can be deployed independently. To enforce strict separation of concerns, each agent is functionally locked to its domain and cannot perform tasks outside of it (e.g., an Audit Agent cannot compile code).1. Sentry (Audit Agent)Role: Dedicated Security & Compliance. Function: Monitors dependencies and source code for vulnerabilities. It operates on a read-only basis regarding the codebase but has write access to security logs. Capabilities:Periodic Scanning: Can be configured to wake up and scan on a cron schedule.Event-Driven: Triggers automatically on-file-create or on-lockfile-change.Isolation: Cannot trigger builds or run code.# Example: Spawn a Sentry agent that runs every hour AND on new file creation
// fusion agent start --role audit --trigger "cron:0 * * * *" --watch "src/**/*"
// 
// 2. Forge (Build Agent)Role: Pure Artifact Generation. Function: Resolves dependency graphs and compiles source code into binaries or libraries. Capabilities:Flux-Resolve Host: Manages the GPU-accelerated SAT solver.Artifact Caching: optimized for writing to the ./target directory.Isolation: Cannot execute the binaries it builds. It hands off artifacts to the Drive agent.# Example: dedicated build server mode (Forge)
// fusion agent start --role build --target release
// 
// 3. Drive (Run Agent)Role: Execution & Testing Environment. Function: Consumes artifacts from the Forge to run tests or launch the final application. Capabilities:Sandboxing: Runs processes in isolated namespaces.Test Orchestration: manages unit tests, integration tests, and benchmarks.Isolation: Cannot compile code. If artifacts are missing, it returns a DependencyError rather than attempting a build.# Example: Run tests strictly using existing artifacts (Drive mode)
// fusion agent start --role run --mode test-only
// 
// 4. Nexus (Intelligence Agent)Role: Analysis & Telemetry. Function: Powers the LSP (Language Server Protocol) and static analysis (fusion check). Capabilities:Zero-Copy Analysis: Reads memory directly from the Forge's cache if available.Deep Lints: Performs semantic analysis without code generation.Isolation: Read-only access to the project. Cannot modify files or run binaries.# Example: Start the Nexus agent for IDE integration
// fusion agent start --role intelligence --port 9000
// 
// 5. Developer GuideSystem ArchitectureThe system is built on four pillars interacting via a central Arc<RwLock<FusionState>>.Orchestrator (fusion_unified_main.rs):Manages the lifecycle state machine (Idle -> Resolving -> Auditing -> Checking -> Compiling -> Running).Handles language dispatch (Fusion Compiler vs Rustc Wrapper).Flux-Resolve (Builder):Uses VSIDS heuristics for SAT solving.Supports resolving hybrid dependency graphs (Fusion packages depending on Rust crates).Auditor (fusion_security_audit.rs):Hooks directly into the resolver's iteration loop.Queries an in-memory database of RustSec advisories.Intelligence Server (fusion_lsp_server.rs):Provides autocompletion and diagnostics for both Fusion and Rust.L1 Cache: A DashMap storing rendered response strings.Building Fusion from Source# 1. Clone
// git clone [https://github.com/fusion-lang/fusion](https://github.com/fusion-lang/fusion)
// cd fusion
// 
// # 2. Build the CUDA Kernel (Optional)
// nvcc -ptx src/cuda_sat_kernel.cu -o kernel.ptx
// 
// # 3. Build the Binary
// cargo build --release --features="cuda"
// 
// # 4. Run Tests
// cargo test
// 
// CI/CD IntegrationFusion is designed to be the only tool needed in CI for both Fusion and Rust pipelines.GitHub Actions Example:steps:
//   - uses: actions/checkout@v3
//   - name: Install Fusion
//     run: curl -fsSL [https://fusion.dev/install](https://fusion.dev/install) | sh
//   - name: Run Pipeline
//     run: fusion run --headless
//     # Automatically handles mixed language builds
// 
// 6. Technical SheetSystem Requirements| Component | Minimum | Recommended | Notes || OS | Linux (Kernel 5.4+), Windows 10+, macOS 12+ | Linux (Kernel 6.x) | Best I/O performance on Linux io_uring. || CPU | 2 Cores | 8+ Cores | Resolver scales linearly with core count. || RAM | 4 GB | 16 GB | Entire dependency graph and HIR are held in RAM. || Storage | HDD | NVMe SSD | Required for artifact caching speed. || GPU | N/A | NVIDIA GTX 1060+ | Required only if project > 10k dependencies. |DependenciesRust Crate: tokio (Async Runtime), dashmap (Concurrent Maps), serde (Serialization).External: libssl (for auditing DB updates).Drivers: NVIDIA CUDA Drivers (v520+) for hardware acceleration features.Security StandardsCryptography: SHA-256 used for all lockfile checksums and CAS addressing.Transport: All registry downloads occur over TLS 1.3.Isolation: The run command spawns child processes with reduced privileges (on supported OS).
